   30.      1
   31.      1// jslint(source, option_dict, global_list) is a function that takes 3
   32.      1// arguments. The second two arguments are optional.
   33.      1
   34.      1//      source          A text to analyze.
   35.      1//      option_dict     An object whose keys correspond to option names.
   36.      1//      global_list     An array of strings containing global variables that
   37.      1//                      the file is allowed readonly access.
   38.      1
   39.      1// jslint returns an object containing its results. The object contains a lot
   40.      1// of valuable information. It can be used to generate reports. The object
   41.      1// contains:
   42.      1
   43.      1//      directives: an array of directive comment tokens.
   44.      1//      edition: the version of JSLint that did the analysis.
   45.      1//      exports: the names exported from the module.
   46.      1//      froms: an array of strings representing each of the imports.
   47.      1//      functions: an array of objects that represent all functions
   48.      1//              declared in the file.
   49.      1//      global: an object representing the global object. Its .context property
   50.      1//              is an object containing a property for each global variable.
   51.      1//      id: "(JSLint)"
   52.      1//      json: true if the file is a JSON text.
   53.      1//      lines: an array of strings, the source.
   54.      1//      module: true if an import or export statement was used.
   55.      1//      ok: true if no warnings were generated. This is what you want.
   56.      1//      option: the option argument.
   57.      1//      property: a property object.
   58.      1//      stop: true if JSLint was unable to finish. You don't want this.
   59.      1//      tokens: an array of objects representing the tokens in the file.
   60.      1//      tree: the token objects arranged in a tree.
   61.      1//      warnings: an array of warning objects. A warning object can contain:
   62.      1//          name: "JSLintError"
   63.      1//          column: A column number in the file.
   64.      1//          line: A line number in the file.
   65.      1//          code: A warning code string.
   66.      1//          message: The warning message string.
   67.      1//          a: Exhibit A.
   68.      1//          b: Exhibit B.
   69.      1//          c: Exhibit C.
   70.      1//          d: Exhibit D.
   71.      1
   72.      1// jslint works in several phases. In any of these phases, errors might be
   73.      1// found. Sometimes JSLint is able to recover from an error and continue
   74.      1// parsing. In some cases, it cannot and will stop early. If that should happen,
   75.      1// repair your code and try again.
   76.      1
   77.      1// Phases:
   78.      1
   79.      1// PHASE 1. Split <source> by newlines into <line_list>.
   80.      1// PHASE 2. Lex <line_list> into <token_list>.
   81.      1// PHASE 3. Parse <token_list> into <token_tree> using the Pratt-parser.
   82.      1// PHASE 4. Walk <token_tree>, traversing all nodes of the tree. It is a
   83.      1//          recursive traversal. Each node may be processed on the way down
   84.      1//          (preaction) and on the way up (postaction).
   85.      1// PHASE 5. Check whitespace between tokens in <token_list>.
   86.      1
   87.      1// jslint can also examine JSON text. It decides that a file is JSON text if
   88.      1// the first token is "[" or "{". Processing of JSON text is much simpler than
   89.      1// the processing of JavaScript programs. Only the first three phases are
   90.      1// required.
   91.      1
   92.      1// WARNING: JSLint will hurt your feelings.
   93.      1
   94.      1/*jslint beta, node*/
   95.      1
   96.      1/*property
   97.      1    causes, console_log,
   98.      1    global_list,
   99.      1    log,
  100.      1    max, min, mode_report, mode_vim_plugin,
  101.      1    process_argv,
  102.      1    report,
  103.      1    stringify,
  104.      1    test_cause, trace,
  105.      1    writeFile,
  106.      1    JSLINT_BETA, a, all, argv, arity, artifact, assign, async,
  107.      1    b, beta, bind, bitwise, block, body, browser, c, calls, catch, catch_list,
  108.      1    catch_stack, cjs_module, cjs_require, cli, closer, closure, code, column,
  109.      1    concat, console_error, constant, context, convert, couch, create, cwd, d,
  110.      1    dead, default, devel, directive, directive_list, directive_quiet,
  111.      1    directives, disrupt, dot, edition, ellipsis, else, endsWith, env, error,
  112.      1    eval, every, exec, execArgv, exit, export_dict, exports, expression, extra,
  113.      1    file, fileURLToPath, filter, finally, flag, for, forEach, formatted_message,
  114.      1    free, freeze, from, froms, fud, function_list, function_stack, functions,
  115.      1    getset, global, global_dict, id, identifier, import, import_list, inc,

  119.      1    map, margin, match, message, meta, mode_cli, mode_json, mode_module,
  120.      1    mode_noop, mode_property, mode_shebang, mode_stop, module, name, names,
  121.      1    node, now, nr, nud, ok, open, opening, option, option_dict, order, padStart,
  122.      1    parameters, parent, pop, process_exit, promises, property, property_dict,
  123.      1    push, quote, readFile, readdir, reduce, repeat, replace, resolve, role,
  124.      1    search, shebang, signature, single, slice, some, sort, source, split, stack,
  125.      1    stack_trace, startsWith, statement, stop, stop_at, switch, syntax_dict,
  126.      1    tenure, test, test_internal_error, this, thru, token, token_global,
  127.      1    token_list, token_nxt, token_tree, tokens, tree, trim, trimRight, try, type,
  128.      1    unordered, url, used, value, variable, versions, warn, warn_at, warning,
  129.      1    warning_list, warnings, white, wrapped, readonly
  130.      1*/

  433.   1053    function warn(code, the_token, a, b, c, d) {
  434.   1053
  435.   1053// Same as warn_at, except the warning will be associated with a specific token.
  436.   1053// If there is already a warning on this token, suppress the new one. It is
  437.   1053// likely that the first warning will be the most meaningful.

  444.    368            (the_token.from || 0) + jslint_fudge,
  445.    806            a || artifact(the_token),
  446.   1053            b,
  447.   1053            c,
  448.   1053            d
  449.   1053        );
  450.    869        if (the_token.warning === undefined) {
  451.    869            the_token.warning = the_warning;
  452.    869        } else {
  453.    184            warning_list.pop();
  454.    184        }

  458.   1359    function warn_at(code, line, column, a, b, c, d) {
  459.   1359
  460.   1359// Report an error at some line and column of the program. The warning object
  461.   1359// resembles an exception.
  462.   1359
  463.   1359        let mm;
  464.   1359        let warning = Object.assign(empty(), {
  465.   1359            a,
  466.   1359            b,
  467.   1359            c,
  468.   1359            code,
  469.   1359
  470.   1359// Fudge column numbers in warning message.
  471.   1359
  472.     25            column: column || jslint_fudge,
  473.   1359            d,
  474.   1359            line,
  475.   1359            line_source: "",
  476.   1359            name: "JSLintError"
  477.   1359        }, line_list[line]);
  478.   1359        warning.column = Math.max(
  479.   1359            Math.min(warning.column, warning.line_source.length),
  480.   1359            jslint_fudge
  481.   1359        );
  482.    887        test_cause(code, b || a, warning.column);
  483.   1359        switch (code) {
  484.   1359

 3520.   9215        }) {
 3521.   9120            earlier = context[id] || earlier;

 3530.      4            }

 3833.  58117    function parse_expression(rbp, initial) {
 3834.  58117
 3835.  58117// This is the heart of JSLINT, the Pratt parser. In addition to parsing, it
 3836.  58117// is looking for ad hoc lint patterns. We add .fud to Pratt's model, which is
 3837.  58117// like .nud except that it is only used on the first token of a statement.
 3838.  58117// Having .fud makes it much easier to define statement-oriented languages like
 3839.  58117// JavaScript. I retained Pratt's nomenclature.
 3840.  58117// They are elements of the parsing method called Top Down Operator Precedence.
 3841.  58117
 3842.  58117// .nud     Null denotation
 3843.  58117// .fud     First null denotation
 3844.  58117// .led     Left denotation
 3845.  58117//  lbp     Left binding power
 3846.  58117//  rbp     Right binding power
 3847.  58117
 3848.  58117// It processes a nud (variable, constant, prefix operator). It will then
 3849.  58117// process leds (infix operators) until the bind powers cause it to stop. It
 3850.  58117// returns the expression's parse tree.
 3851.  58117
 3852.  58117        let left;
 3853.  58117        let the_symbol;
 3854.  58117
 3855.  58117// Statements will have already advanced, so advance now only if the token is
 3856.  58117// not the first of a statement.
 3857.  58117
 3858.  45859        if (!initial) {
 3859.  45859            advance();
 3860.  45859        }
 3861.  58117        the_symbol = syntax_dict[token_now.id];
 3862.  25043        if (the_symbol !== undefined && the_symbol.nud !== undefined) {
 3863.  24992
 3864.  24992// test_cause:
 3865.  24992// ["0", "parse_expression", "symbol", "", 0]
 3866.  24992
 3867.  24992            test_cause("symbol");
 3868.  24992            left = the_symbol.nud();
 3869.  33125        } else if (token_now.identifier) {
 3870.  33125
 3871.  33125// test_cause:
 3872.  33125// ["aa", "parse_expression", "identifier", "", 0]
 3873.  33125
 3874.  33125            test_cause("identifier");
 3875.  33125            left = token_now;
 3876.  33125            left.arity = "variable";
 3877.  33125        } else {
 3878.  33125
 3879.  33125// test_cause:
 3880.  33125// ["!", "parse_expression", "unexpected_a", "(end)", 1]
 3881.  33125// ["/./", "parse_expression", "unexpected_a", "/", 1]
 3882.  33125// ["let aa=`${}`;", "parse_expression", "unexpected_a", "}", 11]
 3883.  33125
 3884.  33125            return stop("unexpected_a", token_now);
 3885.  58075        }
 3886.  58075
 3887.  58075// Parse/loop through each symbol in expression.
 3888.  58075
 3889.  96363        while (true) {
 3890.  96363            the_symbol = syntax_dict[token_nxt.id];
 3891.  96363            if (
 3892.  96363                the_symbol === undefined
 3893.  96363                || the_symbol.led === undefined
 3894.  96363                || the_symbol.lbp <= rbp
 3895.  96363            ) {
 3896.  96363                break;
 3897.  96363            }
 3898.  96363            advance();
 3899.  96363            left = the_symbol.led(left);
 3900.  96363        }
 3901.  58064        return left;
 3902.  58064    }
